e paths inside `text`/`content` strings, and sufficiently varied paths such as long Svelte/component paths can cross the entropy threshold and become `[REDACTED:entropy]`, losing useful review/debug context. A small conservative path-shape check outside path fields, for candidates starting with `/`, `./`, or `../` and without base64 markers, would reduce over-redaction without adding dependencies.\\\" file=\\\"/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/redaction.rs\\\" start=288 end=292 priority=3 confidence=0.72}\\n\\nI did not find wording in the nearby POC docs that promises publication-grade secrecy; the docs and CLI warning still frame transcript inclusion as local, opt-in, and risky. I did not run the Rust test suite; this was a focused privacy/security review with source inspection and a couple of ad hoc heuristic checks.\"}}\n</subagent_notification>","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-07T16:31:21.718Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"message","role":"user","content":[{"type":"input_text","text":"<subagent_notification>\n{\"agent_path\":\"[REDACTED:entropy]\",\"status\":{\"completed\":\"Found three issues.\\n\\n::code-comment{title=\\\"[P2] Sensitive field names do not force redaction\\\" body=\\\"The redactor receives `field_name`, but only uses it for path and Git-hash preservation. Values under keys like `password`, `token`, `api_key`, `authorization`, or `secret` can be stored unchanged when they are short, low-entropy, dictionary-like, or UUID-shaped. For a transcript redaction guard, structured secret labels should override the entropy/non-secret heuristics with a small local denylist and tests; no larger framework needed.\\\" file=\\\"/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/redaction.rs\\\" start=118 end=124 priority=2 confidence=0.87}\\n\\n::code-comment{title=\\\"[P2] Embedded UUIDs are disclosed inside otherwise redacted tokens\\\" body=\\\"`protected_spans()` preserves any UUID range even when the surrounding candidate is being treated as risky. The existing `sk-<uuid>-<random>` test shows the UUID is intentionally left in the stored transcript. That can leak account/session/tenant identifiers or credential components for token formats that embed UUIDs. A safer POC-sized rule would only preserve UUIDs when the whole candidate is a UUID or when it has an approved ID label, and redact the whole candidate otherwise.\\\" file=\\\"/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/redaction.rs\\\" start=173 end=176 priority=2 confidence=0.78}\\n\\n::code-comment{title=\\\"[P3] Path preservation is too field-dependent\\\" body=\\\"`is_obvious_path()` only preserves slashy candidates when the JSON field name is path-like. Agent transcripts often mention file paths inside `text`/`content` strings, and sufficiently varied paths such as long Svelte/component paths can cross the entropy threshold and become `[REDACTED:entropy]`, losing useful review/debug context. A small conservative path-shape check outside path fields, for candidates starting with `/`, `./`, or `../` and without base64 markers, would reduce over-redaction without adding dependencies.\\\" file=\\\"/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/redaction.rs\\\" start=288 end=292 priority=3 confidence=0.72}\\n\\nI did not find wording in the nearby POC docs that promises publication-grade secrecy; the docs and CLI warning still frame transcript inclusion as local, opt-in, and risky. I did not run the Rust test suite; this was a focused privacy/security review with source inspection and a couple of ad hoc heuristic checks.\"}}\n</subagent_notification>"}]}}}